Y1  - 2012 Dec
T1  - Persistent pelvic pain: rising to the challenge.
SP  - 502-7
DO  - 10.1111/j.1479-828X.2012.01473.x
AB  - Persistent pelvic pain is a common condition, with up to 20% of those affected  reporting severe pain. Once end organ disease has been assessed, further  investigations should be minimised. Persistent pelvic pain as a hyperalgesic  neuropathic pain condition must be considered in the differential diagnosis. A  multidisciplinary assessment and management plan, prepared by the co-ordinating  gynaecologist in consultation with the general practitioner, physiotherapist and  psychologist (with gastroenterological, urological and pain medicine specialist  input as deemed appropriate), is strongly recommended.
