TY  - JOUR
ID  - 18054151
VL  - 25
IS  - 4
Y1  - 2007 Dec
T1  - Interventional approaches to pain management.
SP  - 883-98, viii
AB  - This article reviews the evidence for several common interventional techniques  for the treatment of chronic pain, including: intraspinal delivery of analgesics,  reversible blockade with local anesthetics, augmentation with spinal cord  stimulation, and ablation with radiofrequency energy or neurolytic agents. The  role of these techniques is defined within the framework of a multidisciplinary  approach to the neurobehavioral syndrome of chronic pain. Challenges to the study  of the analgesic efficacy of procedural interventions are explored, as are the  practical issues raised by their clinical implementation, with the aim of helping  nonspecialist physicians identify the patients most likely to benefit from these  approaches.
